ndered obsolete.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p></li></ol><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-=
size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">With those companies&#82=
17; product cadence and 5.9 million customers ripe for the picking, many of=
 whom have moved online during the pandemic, I like their odds. When they d=
o, they&#8217;ll limit Bill&#8217;s upside and make it impossible for the c=
ompany to grow into its impossibly high valuation.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"col=
or: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Even a=
fter a wild run in 2020, I&#8217;m still incredibly bullish on tech compani=
es. Product-first companies with built-in distribution will create the next=
 generation of $100 billion+ market cap giants. Bet on those companies, eve=
n if their market caps are much higher than bill.com&#8217;s.</p><p style=
=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"=
>As for bill.com? I&#8217;m not shorting, because shorting anything in a ma=
rket like this is asking to burn money, and there&#8217;s always the risk t=
hat one of the old guard sees a younger version of itself in bill.com&#8217=
;s product and buys it.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Instead, I&#8217;m considering se=
